      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>349</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0021</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0021.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal">Orthonormal</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A set of vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> in an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0012.xml" addr="FA-0012" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link> is said to be orthonormal if:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Each vector has unit norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||e_i|| = 1]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Different vectors are orthogonal to each other: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i \neq  j]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, a set of vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is orthonormal if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = \delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0011.xml" addr="FA-0011" title="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Orthonormal sets have several important properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>They are linearly independent</fr:li>
<fr:li>They provide simple formulas for decomposing vectors: If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an orthonormal set and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is a vector in the space, then the projection of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> onto the span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_{\text {span}\{e_i\}}(x) = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-000W.xml" addr="FA-000W" title="Bessel's inequality">Bessel's inequality</fr:link> holds: For any vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _i |\langle  x, e_i \rangle |^2 \leq  ||x||^2]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Orthonormal sets are fundamental in the study of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert spaces</fr:link> and form the basis for many results in functional analysis, such as the theory of Fourier series and orthogonal polynomials.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>350</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001A</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001A.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{u_n : n \in  \mathbb {N}\}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0019.xml" addr="FA-0019" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} a_n u_n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} b_n u_n]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_n = \langle  u_n, x \rangle ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b_n = \langle  u_n, y \rangle ]]></fr:tex>, then</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\langle  x, y \rangle  = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} a_n \bar {b}_n}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Alternatively</fr:strong>: Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> be a Hilbert Space and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}]]></fr:tex> be a countable orthonormal basis of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, then for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\sum _n {|{\langle  u, e_n \rangle }}|^2 = {||u||}^2}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>(In <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000W.xml" addr="FA-000W" title="Bessel's inequality">Bessel's inequality</fr:link>, we only had an inequality <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\leq ]]></fr:tex> in the expression above)</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>351</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000Q</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000Q.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Convergent">Convergent</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_n)]]></fr:tex> in a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is said to converge to a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x_n, x) < ε]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \geq  N]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In this case, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is called the limit of the sequence, and we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \to  \infty ]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } x_n = x]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In functional analysis, there are various notions of convergence depending on the space and the context, including <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Y.xml" addr="FA-000Y" title="Weak Convergence">weak convergence</fr:link>, <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Z.xml" addr="FA-000Z" title="Convergence in norm">convergence in norm</fr:link>, and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0010.xml" addr="FA-0010" title="Pointwise Convergence">pointwise convergence</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>352</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000U</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000U.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hilbert Space">Hilbert Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000N.xml" addr="FA-000N" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0012.xml" addr="FA-0012" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link>. That is, a Hilbert space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0013.xml" addr="FA-0013" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<\cdot ,\cdot >]]></fr:tex> such that the norm defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x|| = \sqrt {<x,x>}]]></fr:tex> makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into a complete metric space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Hilbert spaces extend the methods of linear algebra to infinite-dimensional settings, making them crucial for quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis, and partial differential equations.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex> of square-integrable functions and the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> of square-summable sequences.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>353</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000V</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000V.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthogonal complement">Orthogonal complement</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a subset of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>. The orthogonal complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\perp ]]></fr:tex>, is the set of all vectors in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> that are orthogonal to every vector in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Formally, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\perp  = \{y \in  H : \langle  x, y \rangle  = 0 \text { for all } x \in  S\}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Some important properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S^\perp ]]></fr:tex> is a closed subspace of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(S^\perp )^\perp  = \overline {\text {span}(S)}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {\text {span}(S)}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0014.xml" addr="FA-0014" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H = \overline {\text {span}(S)} \oplus  S^\perp ]]></fr:tex></fr:li>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\oplus ]]></fr:tex> represents the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0015.xml" addr="FA-0015" title="Direct sum">direct sum</fr:link> of subspaces</fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>354</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000T</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000T.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal sequence">Orthonormal sequence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An orthonormal sequence in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(u_n)]]></fr:tex> of vectors in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>1. Each vector has unit norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||u_n|| = 1]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>2. Different vectors are orthogonal to each other: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u_m, u_n \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m \neq  n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, an orthonormal sequence satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u_m, u_n \rangle  = \delta _{mn}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{mn}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0011.xml" addr="FA-0011" title="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>An orthonormal sequence is a fundamental concept in the study of Hilbert spaces and forms the basis for Fourier analysis and many approximation methods.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
</fr:tree>
